Now I've oven-roasted a bunch of crimini and white button mushrooms at 500F with a couple cloves of garlic

Celery, unpeeled carrots, shallots, all in big fat chops, throw them all in the dutch oven with the meat and throw in the roasted mushrooms & garlic and pour the broth over it all, slow cook at 265 for a good long while until the meat is perfect

Goal of the thread: Go out for a walk, or try to get any other form of small exercise (walking stairs for 5 mins for example)
Daily goals can be repeated. Remember to keep score, it can only go up!

>What is this thread for?
Getting better is hard, and sucks. A lot. It does not get easier doing it alone.
Share resources and experiences with combating depression, anxiety, personal issues, achieving or maintaining a healthy weight, etc.
>Why is this thread /lgbt/?
Struggles with mental and physical health are an indisputable part of /lgbt/ life, be it from dysphoria, social pressure, heartbreak, or just unfortunate lifestyle choices.
>Notes to consider:
Please be civil. Shame is your greatest enemy in fighting urges of self abuse (be it sh, drugs, or just self deprecation). Relapsing into bad and unhealthy habits is to be expected, the goal is to increase the average amount of time it takes between relapses. Any improvement is a victory no matter how small. Your worth and right to get better are non-negotiable. And most importantly:
WE ARE NOT THERAPISTS, WE DON'T REPLACE MEDICATION
>Note on advice
Generic advice won't necessarily help you in particular, but for those it does it is an essential foundation to build future progress on, not a miracle cure. Do not underestimate the effects subtle changes to your lifestyle can have. Try first, keep us posted on your progress, build from there.

If any resource below is unhelpful, please let me know. I can't assert their quality on my own.

resources:

Exercise, diet, weight loss/gain: >>>/fit/17018018 (sticky)
NIMH brochures on mental health topics (Depression, BPD, ADHD, etc): https://www.nimh.nih.gov/health/publications
ED: https://www.eatingdisorderhope.com/treatment-for-eating-disorders

General advice from Anons: https://0x0.st/o5Og.txt

we currently lack (mental) health resources.
Suggestions and debate for which to include encouraged!

Additional resources:
Get started with weight loss (courtesy of /fit/fat/):
>What do I do first?
1. Read https://physiqonomics.com/fat-loss/
2. Calculate your Body Fat Percentage: https://fitness.bizcalcs.com/Calculator.asp?Calc=Body-Fat-Navy
3. Calculate your TDEE: https://www.sailrabbit.com/bmr/
Remember to use bodyfat% and use Katch-McArdle Formula with sedentary settings or your TDEE will be too high.
4. Plan your weight loss: https://www.losertown.org/eats/cal.php
5. Track your nutrition with MyFitnessPal (better for packaged food), Cronometer (better for generic food/macros) or LoseIt (great for both).

Today I included all goals we had in any thread so far, for more choice <3

- Open your window for 10-20 minutes
- pick up items on the floor for 5 minutes
- write down one thing you are grateful for (from abstract things to something like a cute image you saw)
- if you have a bad habit, try making it more inconvenient (putting things in hard to reach places for example)

- eat a meal
- read one page of a book or manga you have been putting off

- make your bed

>>28865768
Tell me more, anon. The first thing you need to know is that, as the OP says, relapsing is part of healing. These roadblocks are natural and frequent, especially in the beginning. The problem usually lies in what conclusion you draw from them, because they reinforce the idea of struggling not being worth it. You must view these days as isolated exceptions, and disregard the decisions made that day as hiccups. That isn't easy, but you can do it.
>>28865905
That's a BMI of roughly 21 (good) if I did the math right, and you seem healthy and physically fit. In that case it really is just your self image that is an issue. Self image can be such a bitch to work on, and I can't think of a one size fits all recommendation. But one thing that you need to keep in mind about looks is that perspective and aesthetics are not entirely rational things, and that it is sometimes for the best to recall that you can mold your views as time passes more by habituation than by trying to argue your way out of feeling like that.

posts.com:
>>28850175

Short answer: maybe, if you're unlucky (you aren't, you already have D cups) or dosing wrong (no way to know how your body would prefer prog administered to maximize growth)

Long answer: probably not

Prog is part of the natural cis female cycle, starting at the first period, long before breast development is anywhere near finished. Prog has been observed to modulate the expression and behavior of estrogen receptors. If I'm remembering correctly, in rabbit models large spikes have been shown to result in a (very) temporary downregulation of estrogen receptors on the surface of breast cells. Our reproductive systems are quite different, but this MAY be an argument in favor of cycling prog, as it also results in a burst of prolactin which makes the tissue more sensitive estrogen after prog levels dip. The best thing to do if you want to maximize breast growth, IMO, is to get all of the growth you can out of just E before staying on prog long term, as everyone's body will respond differently to it. If you want more facial feminization, prog typically accelerates those changes.

>>28852665
Losing weight with a low caloric intake can reduce breast growth. Cardio can increase growth hormone levels and causes the loss of visceral fat. Visceral fat is important for hormone regulation and too much of it can have a negative impact on feminization.

The link I've included has a case study of how to lose muscle when transitioning. The exercise regimen for burning visceral fat is the same. Diet instructions are similar. If you don't want to lose muscle, too, just make sure you eat a healthy amount of protein instead of cutting it like the article describes.

If you're trying to lose weight, I suggest you try to retain your muscle until you've lost the fat you want. Losing muscle will reduce your metabolism and make it harder to lose fat in the future.

I feel like I should maybe clarify something, I was assuming you were a hardcore gym rat before. The natural state for any physical body is "use it or lose it". Imagine you're constantly losing a small percentage of your strength every day. Normal activity, like walking down the hall and taking out the trash causes you to build a very small amount of strength. Working out does a lot more. If you did nothing but lay in bed, staring at the ceiling, the loss would stack up quickly and you'd notice it after a few days. Just doing that little bit of housework helps to counteract this a lot. Testosterone made it so the rate that you lose strength at was low. Without male levels of T, the rate you lose strength at will be a lot higher, so you need to do more just to counteract the loss and even more to bulk. If you were already ripped you'd probably notice yourself plateau a bit.

"The red umbrella, global symbol of sex workers' solidarity, was used for the first time in 2001 in Venice during the 49th Art Biennale. On this occasion, a group of sex workers marched through the streets of Venice with red umbrellas as part of the "prostitute pavilion" and the CODE: RED installation by Slovenian artist Tadej Pogačar.

The march was led by activist Daniela Mannu and organized by the non-profit organization Committee for the Civil Rights of Prostitutes (CDCP) with Carla Corso as chairwoman. It drew attention to the poor working conditions and human rights violations that sex workers often have had to face. Since then, the red umbrella has become an icon and international emblem of sex workers' rights around the world. It symbolises protection from the abuse and intolerance faced by sex workers, and stands forstrength and resistence."

That doesn't mean that you're not trans, although you might not be trans. I'm not trying to tell you that you are or pinkpill you or anything like that. But, like, 100% certainty is a lot to have on something more fuzzy like this. I think there will always be a speck of doubt somewhere, especially because of what society says about us, it gets to you. But like you can ask yourself some questions in your head, stuff like, "would I press a button that made it so I was me but if I was born as a cis girl and everyone acted like I always was a girl?" or "would I transition if I knew I'd pass and it was totally socially acceptable?" or even like "if I took a couple tests and they said that I'm most likely (male/female/trans/cis (think separately for each one)), how would it make me feel?" or "would I rather be an average and decent looking cis woman or the hottest man on earth?" stuff like that. I think basically everyone who transitions, unless they're completely unhinged, worries about the social consequences and all of the pain and effort that goes into transition and about if they'll pass or not. It's just like, once the pain of how they're living surpasses their fear of what could happen, they don't care as much anymore and they transition.

It's heavy and it's a lot of processing to do but I don't think I'd just say you're definitely not based on that. Like, if you pressed the hypothetical "turn into a cis girl" button from that question...
